Bring a #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{125%g} and cook until tender, ~{4%mins}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} or #wok{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{240%g} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Fry, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{5-6%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Meanwhile, halve the @plums{2}, remove the stone and slice the flesh of each plum into 12 thin wedges.

Trim the @pak choi{1}, then separate the leaves. Cut each leaf in half lengthways down the middle.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Lower the heat to medium and add the plums and @sugar{1%tsp} to the chicken.

Stir-fry until the plums start to colour, ~{1-2%mins}.

Stir in the garlic, @ginger puree{7.5%g} and as many @chilli flakes{1%pinch} as you'd like (add less if you'd prefer things milder).

Stir-fry for ~{1%min} more.

Add the pak choi and stir-fry until just soft, ~{1-2%mins}.

Stir in the @hoisin sauce{32%g}, @ketjap manis{25%g} and @water{2%tbsp}, ensuring everything's well coated.

Add the cooked noodles to the pan. Stir together and cook until everything's piping hot, ~{1-2%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Share the chicken and plum stir-fry between your #bowls{}.

Scatter over the @salted peanuts{25%g} to finish. Enjoy!